		<div class="page-header">
	      <div class="panel-body">
		      <span style="font-size: larger;">
					<p><b>GLIMPSE</b> is a phasing and imputation method for large-scale low-coverage sequencing studies.</p>
					<p>Main features of the method:</p>
					<ol>
						<li><b>Accurate imputed genotype calls.</b> Our method takes advantage of reference panels (containing thousands of haplotypes) to refine genotypes likelihoods from low-coverage datasets and produce high quality genotype calls.</li>
						<li><b>Accurate phasing.</b> GLIMPSE outputs accurate phased information for the low-coverage sequenced dataset.</li>
						<li><b>Low-coverage sequencing outperforms SNP arrays.</b> 
							Imputation using low-coverage sequencing data is more accurate than SNP array imputation in the full range of allele frequency. 
							Results for <a href="rsquare_eur.html">European</a> and <a href="rsquare_asw.html">African-American</a> populations are interactively available on the website. 
						<li><b>A cost-effective paradigm.</b> GLIMPSE realises whole genome imputation from the HRC reference panel for less than 1$ cost.</li>
					</ol>
		<!-- 			<p>If you use the GLIMPSE in your research work, please cite the following paper:</p>
					<p><a href="">Simone Rubinacci, Diogo Ribeiro, Robin Hofmeister, Olivier Delaneau. TITLE. JOURNAL. 2020.</a></p> -->
					<p>GLIMPSE tools is available under the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MIT_License">MIT licence</a> on the Github repository <a href="https://github.com/odelaneau/GLIMPSE">https://github.com/odelaneau/GLIMPSE</a>.</p>
					<p>GLIMPSE was developed by Simone Rubinacci and Olivier Delaneau at the University of Lausanne, Switzerland.</p>
				</span>
				<br>
